Japanese pastry maker COVID-19 in Sapporo, Hokkaido, has suspended production of its flagship product, "white lovers" , from February 20 as a result of an outbreak of the disease and a drop in the number of Chinese tourists leading to a drop in sales. It's a 40-year-old chocolate-chip cookie popular with Chinese tourists.

The company, founded in 1947, announced that its West Sapporo and Kitahiroshima factories would be closed until March 15, while factories in Sapporo would be closed from March 23 to 27.

"whether production will continue beyond the current shutdown period depends on future conditions, so it is not clear, " said Ishiya. "It is hoped that the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic will be ended as soon as possible. "

Mainland Chinese tourists visiting Japan during the Lunar New Year holiday fell by about 20 percent as the COVID-19 epidemic spread.

The head of Japan's Tourism Agency, Tian Duanhao, said regular flights between Japan and China were down about 70 percent from before the outbreak, adding that "the impact will be felt after February. ".

In 2019,9.59 million Chinese tourists visited Japan, accounting for 30 percent of all tourists to Japan, ranking first among all countries and regions. Assuming zero group tourists in Hokkaido in February and March, it is estimated that tourism spending will be 20 billion yen (1.3 billion yuan) less than a year ago.

In addition, as a result of the increase in the number of confirmed cases in Japan, tourists from other countries may no longer choose Japan as a tourist destination. Foreign visitors to Japan will spend 624.4 billion yen (36.9 billion yuan) less by May this year because of the new coronavirus pneumonia, the LISONA institute estimated on Feb. 12.

Lead researcher Hideyuki Araki, of the LISONA Institute for Comprehensive Research, said: "If the slow-down of the pneumonia epidemic hinders the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics, the impact could increase significantly. "
